We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms and laboratory results suggest acute myeloid leukemia. The low hemoglobin and platelet counts, along with the presence of blasts in the peripheral blood smear, are indicative of a myeloid neoplasm. Chronic myelogenous leukemia and hairy cell leukemia typically have higher leukocyte counts and less pronounced cytopenias. Primary myelofibrosis may present with cytopenias and megakaryocyte proliferation, but the presence of blasts in the peripheral blood smear is not characteristic.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms and laboratory findings are suggestive of acute myeloid leukemia, which is characterized by the presence of immature cells (blast cells) in the peripheral blood and bone marrow. The image shows blast cells with large, round nuclei and scant cytoplasm. Chronic myelogenous leukemia usually has a higher leukocyte count and the presence of Philadelphia chromosome. Hairy cell leukemia would have more mature cells with hair-like projections. Primary myelofibrosis would have increased fibrosis in the bone marrow.
